The Board of County Commissioners is hosting a COVID-19 Education Forum Online--Thursday, September 10 at 5:30-7:00 p.m.
Join online: https://zoom.us/j/92770578873
By phone: 888-475-4499
Meeting ID: 927 7057 8873

A panel of experts from the health and education fields will join the Lewis County Commissioners for the online forum. The event will include a presentation about the pandemic, including current health recommendations around schools, followed by a question-and-answer session.

Those wishing to submit questions are encouraged to do so via email at bocc@lewiscountywa.gov by 3:00 p.m. Sept. 10th.

***Note: this forum is not hosted by Centralia School District***

Reducing our budget for 2020-21 by nearly 22 percent, while preserving equity and minimizing impact to student learning is a challenging task. Here is how the reductions have been made.

The unknown question of the levy election result in August means our district has to draft our budget for next year with the assumption that we will not have those funds.

Lewis County has officially been approved to move to phase 2 of reopening. Under phase 2, citizens are advised to continue to stay home and stay health. Outdoor recreation is permitted with fewer than 5 people from outside your household. Gatherings with 5 or fewer people from outside your household are permitted once per week. Limited non-essential travel is permitted.

Certain businesses may open such as:
Restaurants at 50% or less of capacity, no tables larger than 5. Retail (in-store purchases allowed, with restrictions). Hair and Nail Salons. Barbers. Real estate.

More zoom/Google Classroom meets today! Mrs. Cearns and Turner got their first grade class together to talk about how they're doing with their home learning resources. Edison's kindergarten teachers tried to get their kinders - all of them - together for a visit as well!

Xfinity is also offering their "internet essentials" package to low income famlies for free (to new customers) for the first two months. The plan is usually $9.95 a month.

It may feel like the world has gone upside down. We've created a comprehensive list of learning resources you can use at home to help keep some sort of normal learning routine for your kiddos! These resources align with our curricula and methods, and many may already be familiar to your child.

It is important to remember, this isn't a vacation (even if it is the first day of spring). Helping keep your child's mind in learning mode will help them transition back into the classroom successfully when things get back to "normal."

We're all in this together, and we're here for you!

Resources for middle and high school families are coming soon.

post_text:
Ensuring that our students have continued access to proper nutrition during the shutdown is a goal of our district, Washington State, and the federal government. Sack lunches and breakfasts will be available to all children age 0-18 at each elementary school in Centralia every weekday from 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. Children do not need to be currently enrolled in Centralia schools to receive meals. Lunch and breakfast for the next day will be handed out together. In order to maintain proper social distancing, meals cannot be consumed on-site.

We will monitor demand for this program throughout the closure and, if necessary, take steps to expand availability.

We will monitor demand for this program throughout the closure and, if necessary, take steps to expand availability.

It is with great sadness that we have to share the news that Mr. Darrin Canfield, math and robotics teacher at Centralia High School, has passed away. Mr. Canfield had been a respected teacher, friend, coach, mentor, and colleague at CHS since 1993. He was determined to continue serving students throughout his courageous cancer fight, which spanned more than a decade. He was a nearly constant fixture on the sidelines of our CHS football games as a member of the coaching staff. Darrin was a man of strong principals and good character and he will be dearly missed by his Centralia School District family.

The CHS administration is working to ensure that students and staff are able to access whatever support resources they need during this difficult time.

Our thoughts are with Mr. Canfield's family, friends, students, and co-workers.

post_text:
"How much does Centralia School District spend on the Community Indoor Pool" is a question we hear quite often.
In the current school year we have spent $202,061.31 on the pool facility which includes general maintenance obligations, swim week for students, and the ongoing repair of the spa facility. This is about 0.37% of our annual budget (roughly one third of one percent).

Last year we spent $164,426.31, or 0.32% of our total annual budget.

The pool does receive EP&O levy support for things like maintenance, swim week (3rd grade and CMS students), and use by the CHS swim team.

In recent past years the pool liner has been replaced as a regular maintenance issue. The pool HVAC system was replaced about 7 years ago largely with energy efficiency grants received by the district.

the City of Centralia also contributes to maintenance and upkeep of the indoor pool facility.

The pool was built after a majority of Centralia's voters approved a bond for its construction in the late 1970s.

post_text:
Mr. Pruitt's third graders were using their chromebooks to work on informational writing yesterday. Students can research and write on the same device. Using Google Classroom allows students to submit their assignments electronically, saving both time and printing/paper costs. Teachers can access and grade work from anywhere, and even provide feedback.

Chromebooks fill a huge variety of needs in our district, from testing to daily classwork, intervention support, and research. They have about a 6 year life span, with may devices in use currently approaching the end of manufacturer support, and compatibility with state testing and our assessment apps. Nearly 3/4 of our chromebook inventory will require replacement over the next two years.

Technology purchases, maintenance, and replacement are levy supported. The state does not provide funding for these necessary devices, even though state assessments are now all done online.

Even though per-student revenue from our local levy has fallen by more than $2.2 million since 2017, the programs the levy funds are still there.

The average rate per $1,000 for CSD levies since 2010 is $2.49. The rate for the replacement EP&O levy is $2.50.

The levy supports programs and services that are either not funded or not fully funded by the state or other sources.

post_text:
There's been a lot of conversation about per-pupil funding increases for education. While it's accurate to say per-pupil funding from all sources is up, that's not the whole story. Each revenue source can only be used for specific purposes. Our levy funded programs rely on local revenue because other sources do not fully fund them, or do not fund them at all.

So here's the story of per-pupil funding in terms of our local levy. In 2017-18 our local EP&O levy provided $1,611.15 per student. This year it provides $961.19 per student. That is a decrease of more than 40 percent in two years. This is a result of state legislation that reduced our local levy from $2.83 per $1,000 to $1.50 - without giving our local community a say. We have relied on reserve funds to keep these programs and services in Centralia.

The levy on your ballot is a replacement of the current levy, which expires this year. New legislation allows districts to seek levies up to $2.50 per $1,000, which will allow us to continue to provide our levy-funded programs and services.

Chromebooks are an integral part of academics in Centralia. At every grade level, students use them for classroom lessons, collaboration with peers, communication with teachers, state assessment taking, even preparing and submitting homework assignments. Their average life span is about 6 years of hard work. Our district is approaching a 1:1 ratio of student devices.

In the next two years, more than 75% of our district's chromebooks will require replacement - more than 2,000 of them.

As units become unsupported or simply give way to wear and tear, the EP&O levy helps fund technology purchases, maintenance, and replacement.

#LeviesAreForLearning

CHS has been evacuated due to a small fire - which has been extinguished.

A brand-new milk cooler caught fire, causing smoke in the lobby area. There is no structural damage, and no injury. The malfunctioning cooler has been removed, and students will be allowed back into the building upon approval from Riverside fire.

We will update when more information is available.

post_text:
October is Disability Awareness Month. Jefferson Lincoln was proud to host Mr. Simon Calcavecchia, author of the Adventures of Frank and Mustard series, yesterday. Simon suffered a neck injury in a rugby match that left him paralyzed from the chest down. But he hasn't let that stop him from living life to its fullest!

Not only is he a successful author, Simon is a motivational speaker and disability awareness advocate. His message to the JL community was that they should never let adversity decide what they can accomplish.

Thank you Simon for your powerful message and for sharing your stories (and songs)! And thanks to our Mrs. Downs for helping to arrange this opportunity!

post_text:
Two unplanned fire drills in our schools today that just happened to occur close to each other.

At Edison, flushing of the hydrant outside the school caused a water pressure change or water hammer that created a fault in the sprinkler system. This caused a fire alarm to sound.

At CHS, there was also a water pressure issue in several sections of the fire suppression system. The exact cause has not been determined yet.

Riverside fire responded to both schools. They investigated and declared each school safe to resume classes.

Thank you to Riverside Fire Authority - Centralia, WA for their quick response and assistance. And congratulations to students at both schools for their response to the unplanned fire alarms.

October 11, 2019 at 11:25 PM ·

October 11 is the 25th annual International Day of the Girl Child. It is an awareness day created by the United Nations to draw attention to gender inequality around the world.

Worldwide, millions of young women are denied access to healthcare, education, employment, and basic civil rights on no basis other than their gender. Worse, in the 21st century, young women are still being forced into child marriages and being taken by traffickers. Some of these inequities still exist in our own country.

In Centralia, we believe that the idea that a cap should be placed on a child's level of achievement at birth by virtue of their gender is abhorrent. We are immensely proud of the approximately 1,800 young women in our schools. They are future leaders, business owners, inventors, parents, politicians, educators, and more. They will change the world in ways we haven't even thought of. We can't wait to see everything they accomplish.

October is #Bullying prevention month. Mrs. Fitzgerald (Oakview counselor) visited Mrs. Gonzalez's third grade class to talk about bullying. She uses the Second Step curriculum, which provides grade-level specific lessons about bullying and how it can/should be avoided.

Nationwide, nearly 21% of students report being bullied. Students who experience bullying, and the bullies themselves, are more susceptible to negative effects such as poor academic achievement and low self-esteem.

Centralia High School
September 27, 2019 at 7:23 PM ·

Work on phase 2 of the modernization project at Centralia High School is forging ahead. The updated locker rooms have re-opened for student use, though there is still some work to be completed there.

Coming up, we expect the wood and metal shop areas to reopen this fall, possibly by the end of October. The kitchen is on pace for completion in November. Currently, meals are being prepared and served in alternate locations. The new Gilmore Commons is scheduled for completion in March along with the performing arts center, music rooms, business lab, and sports medicine lab. We can't wait to show off the fully completed project!

post_text: Last week, Mrs. Langan's second grade class worked on a lesson about mindset. A card stock cutout was placed on their tables, and they were asked to cut a shape exactly like it. Mrs. Langan listened closely to comments the students made during the lesson, and then the group discussed whether they had a growth mindset or a fixed mindset.

post_text:
What a great first day! This has been a marathon summer getting three new schools ready to open, re-creating bus routing, moving almost everything in every school. Having all of our favorite amazing students back in our schools makes it all worthwhile. Our staff, community, and construction partners are our heroes for all of the work they have contributed to make it happen.

Here's to new beginnings, new schools, and an awesome new year. Welcome back!

#WeAreCentralia
